spanGrp.span: Let me tell the story about a poor boy.
simpa chara akheh to eh vapate ithọdo varamo
there was a boy, I think his father died.
I think he lived only with his mother.
vanu̠ tuwng akhopām mo khu akheh ha ichọọcha vajerāmo
now with his mom, I think they went to one village
Nu̠ ohǃ Kadol thuwka ve vadanāte
"Motherǃ" he said, "I need to do my needs."
"Go a bit further and do it"
mae hesonseeva dọnu̠ vahason vaheson nāte
"No, go further", she said, and as he went on and on
"Yes" she said, when she saw that he cannot be seen.
vaheson vaheson vaheson nāte atung hate vanu̠te vachun pedohva
As he went on and on, his mother ran away.
nu̠tāng patāng vanu̠ mi inti thuha ahlunnu̠
He became an orphan, and had to wander under other houses
akhopām akhopāmha mi tharka ha kakara ahlun nu̠
mi bu̠ paṭe an paṭe to achungnu̠ chachanu̠ iam chava
and to live picking up food thrown away by others
te mi atum ha kikara hlunu̠ mi
he entered inside a store room
a bag of millet that people hang
and rice that people hang etc.
vasam eh pabā hlu̠nu̠ ate vānhu̠wlva
He made his hair bushy and wiped it with his hair
eh mi intih vāhlun memee thung tuwng samche akheh dunu̠ amato
oh! no, when he wandered under people houses, he found a knife
he cut a bamboo and made a binding wire
lidār kara kara sanu̠ chaṭha kara kara sanu̠ amato joolnu̠ joolnu̠
he made dryer trays and other things and sold it
le kāng pihol akheh to rinchanu̠
he cultivated and then reaped a lot
mi bu̠to te chara chara mi chaṭang vanaphito chara charato achung chānu̠
he picked up some rice that other people were drying
hlivānu̠ am- amathung tuwng vaduh vah
cultivated the field and sowed that rice
and so he became very rich.
chavang to thulolnu̠ vadanāte nahla likaning danu̠ nahlato valichava
as he became very rich, he said "I'll take a wife", and got married
atungbe ṭum kheh khu̠ vaning kum va hlivā khu̠nu̠ va hlivā khu̠nu̠
then the next year he cultivated fields more and more
and he reaped a lot of rice
rinnu̠ vā khe rinnu̠ sal khe rinnu̠ vaju nāte
and pigs and cows and was taking care of them
as he got plenty of it, he said "I'll celebrate"
kanu̠he thọchamo hring kamo oon ningsung
and I'll call my mother, to see whether she is dead or alive
But his mother was already married
hal kara karah to khangpung ipung
There were so many hens and other animals
of many different colours, like grey
vā joso ate irang pong pong vaṭhova
and pigs all of different colours
There was celebration and he danced
My mother left me and my father left me
te adāmnu̠ vadanāte vanu̠to onnu̠ ṭhingnu̠ no
As he danced like that he called his mother and she came
He let her stay in his house.
jọọngte "Nu̠ ohǃ Hal bu̠ṭho kāpe pevah"
In the morning, "Mother, please, feed my hens"
Ni kahal te ne vahmi e choo ṭinṭanso
My hens will have eyes full of dirt.
eeh "Boling hal ti ti" danu̠ kaon pevāno vado nāte
Call my hens for me "Boling's hens, ti-ti-ti"
hal bu̠ṭhọ to sinchongnu̠ jungṭumnu̠ vanu̠to
His mother carried the rice and went down.
"Boling hal ti ti ti" vada nāte
Hal to e nājah avang chun jenu̠
vadanāte vaning thinu̠ ṭahcha ve vaṭahnāte
so she got upset and cried. As she cried
"Nu̠ oh, dāki iṭah vati me?" vadanāte. "Ahal oh"
"Mother, why are you crying?", he asked. "Your chicken...
iṭah vaning veǃ" vadava vaning jānu̠ iṭahcha varende
so I am crying", she answered, but she cried because of feeling ashamed.
caught his hen and cut its wings
"Nu̠, atungte vā bu̠ kāpe pevano" vadonāte
Then he said "Mom, feed my pigs."
She prepared food for the pigs.
"ing Boling vā cho cho" danu̠ kāon peva no
vavah to eh nādidihnu̠ rāng pongpongnu̠
His pigs were very big and of different colours.
Big gray ones and black ones, many came there.
ṭah khu̠cha danāte "Nu̠, dāki iṭahcha vati moe?" vadanāte
She cried again, and he asked "Mom, why are you crying?"
avah hmi oh vābu̠ kape teoh
Your pig's tale, as I was giving them food
Eh khekheha vāhlun na kahmi kāthun pedoonu̠
as they were wandering around, they cut my eyes
so he cut off the pig's tale
sal pachọ kāpe pevā danu̠ sal to pachọ to vapeva
he said "Give salt to my cattle'', he gave salt to the cows.
ho ho ho adanu̠ kāonpe vā no amaso
Saying "ho-ho-ho", call them for me, OK?.
kasal eh vahmi eh choo ṭinṭan naka no
my cattle will have eyes full of dirt.
jo jo jo jo jo pachọ ho ho pachọ ho ho" danu̠ vaon nāte
irāng oh ivum oh nājah ṭhingkhu̠nu̠ vadanāte
Many cows came, some colourful, some black.
ding vame dọnu̠ pachọ kapenāte oh vānā
He asked "What happened?" "As I was giving them salt, a cow's ear...
damo, kahmi kāsu̠ pedo khu̠nu̠ oh vadọkhu̠va
kanu̠ hmi thina vasu̠ vajemo dachongnu̠
always brush against my mother's eyes?" said he pretending
Which cow you like the most?
take a look and choose one
sal ānape chā ningeh akoongha apashuvā
"Bind the cow that I gave you to your waist"
as he said, she bound it on her waist
she bound it with the thread
vavang nāte atung ne su̠ku̠ng avanpha tiing tiing
as she started going, he said "Now, eh? just before reaching the gate"
hueh adu̠m rung vāno nu̠ vadanāte
As she went... I think they were a bit foolish
vakoong hatuwng salto pakolnu̠ sanglā vāhang loonthung
She bound the cow to her waist and went uphill
hueh to vadu̠m rung nāte sal to aphinu̠ne
She gave a wistle. The cow got angry.
It pulled her down and the mother died.
vadanāte mi anu̠ thọ chave danu̠
The people told him: "Your mother has died."
atung hate Boling ku̠wng tuwng vapajā nāte
